WEBVTT

00:00:00.270 --> 00:00:02.870
<v Instructor>Okay, so just a quick note on AWS abuse</v>

00:00:02.870 --> 00:00:05.350
which is something that can come up in the exam.

00:00:05.350 --> 00:00:08.600
So in case you are suspecting some resources

00:00:08.600 --> 00:00:10.430
in AWS, for example, some IPs

00:00:10.430 --> 00:00:12.620
or some institute instances that are used

00:00:12.620 --> 00:00:14.530
for abusive or illegal purposes,

00:00:14.530 --> 00:00:17.070
then you can report it to AWS.

00:00:17.070 --> 00:00:20.010
And so these kind of abusive and prohibited behaviors

00:00:20.010 --> 00:00:22.120
are going to be around spam, so for example,

00:00:22.120 --> 00:00:25.700
you receive undesired emails from IPs owned by AWS,

00:00:25.700 --> 00:00:28.840
websites and forums spammed by AWS resources,

00:00:28.840 --> 00:00:31.420
port scanning, for example, someone is trying a port scan

00:00:31.420 --> 00:00:34.060
from AWS which is not accepted,

00:00:34.060 --> 00:00:36.160
a DDoS attack, intrusion attempts,

00:00:36.160 --> 00:00:38.660
so someone is trying to logging onto your resources,

00:00:38.660 --> 00:00:41.640
or for example, someone that hosts questionable

00:00:41.640 --> 00:00:43.470
or copyrighted content

00:00:43.470 --> 00:00:45.830
and so therefore it's illegal content hosted on AWS,

00:00:45.830 --> 00:00:47.940
you can also contact the abuse team.

00:00:47.940 --> 00:00:51.010
And finally distributing malware is also prohibited.

00:00:51.010 --> 00:00:54.270
So you cannot host malware on AWS obviously, right?

00:00:54.270 --> 00:00:56.960
So in case you suspect any of these activities,

00:00:56.960 --> 00:00:59.420
what you should be doing is to contact the abuse team.

00:00:59.420 --> 00:01:01.610
So there is either an online form

00:01:01.610 --> 00:01:05.570
or you can just send them an email at abuse@amazonaws.com

00:01:05.570 --> 00:01:08.610
and that's all you need to know for this in the exam.

00:01:08.610 --> 00:01:11.210
Okay, that's it. I will see you in the next lecture.